serviceDimensions.name: Compliance Activity
serviceDimensions.description: Compliance services in this category include assisting the community that need help to meet their lodgment obligations through gentle reminders (such as first reminder letters) through to more severe strategies such as hard final notices, penalties and compliance reviews and audits or legal action. Compliance activities in this cluster seek to ensure lodgments are made within expected timeframes and to also check the accuracy of lodgments - key to ensure we are fairly administering the tax system.

serviceDimensions.name: Education & Support
serviceDimensions.description: The Education component covers all services in which the Tax Office proactively provides the community about tax and superannuation obligations. Generally these services have an education focus with the aim to influence voluntary compliance - making it easier to comply through self-registration activities. This could include items that are sent out to the general community such as media releases, brochures issued through schools, TV or radio advertisements, or speaker events. Additionally this also includes educational communication campaigns targeted at specific groups - for example, we may identify that everyone receiving FTB part A may be eligible for Education Tax Refund, so a mail out could be sent to those people specifically. The Support component covers all advice the Tax Office provides in response to requests from the community seeking advice to help them meet their tax and super obligations or request refunds. Advice could either be general in nature (eg. Can you tell me how CGT works?) or could be related specifically to the customer's personal circumstances (eg. Can you tell me how I can calculate my rental deductions?). Providing efficient accurate advice helps to fulfil our responsibilities to the community as per the Tax Payer's Charter and is key in promoting voluntary compliance through assisting those who are trying to meet their obligations.

serviceDimensions.name: Lodgment Service
serviceDimensions.description: The Lodgment cluster encompasses all services which require the community to lodge information (usually via a form) to the Tax Office to report what their current situation is (usually their income & expenses) to accurately identify what their tax and superannuation obligations are or if they are due for a refund or payment. Timeliness and accuracy of lodgments from the community is crucial in a self assessment system, which is why this cluster also includes lodgment support services to assist the community that need help to meet their lodgment obligation through deferrals and suspensions.

serviceDimensions.name: Payment & Accounting
serviceDimensions.description: The Payment cluster covers all services that facilitate the community to either make or receive payments to accurately settle their tax and superannuation obligations. This cluster also contains services to perform account maintenance such as credit transfers or remission of a penalty which when actioned, will adjust the customer's account to ensure it is reflecting an accurate balance to allow for either making or receiving payment. In this cluster compliance services help the community to comply through services such as payment arrangements.

serviceDimensions.name: Registration Services
serviceDimensions.description: The Registration cluster encompasses all services for the community to register themselves for their tax and super obligations and to maintain these registrations accurately as their situation changes. These services enable businesses to register for taxation purposes, and to maintain their registration - this includes their Australian Business Number (ABN) and other roles that relate to specific taxation obligations (e.g. GST, PAYGW, etc.). The community is expected to proactively register themselves accurately. Accurate registration allows for accurate level of compliance.

serviceDimensions.name: Individual
serviceDimensions.description: An individual. If an individual operates their business as a sole trader, the individual trade on their own and control and manage the business. The individual is legally responsible for all aspects of the business - debts and losses cannot be shared.

serviceDimensions.name: Company
serviceDimensions.description: An incorporated company is a distinct legal entity, regulated by the Australian Securities & Investments Commission (ASIC). A company is a complex business structure, with higher set-up costs and administrative costs because of additional reporting requirements. A company's operations are controlled by its directors and the company is owned by its shareholders.

serviceDimensions.name: Partnership
serviceDimensions.description: For tax purposes, a partnership is an association of people who carry on a business as partners or receive income jointly. A formal partnership agreement is common, but not essential. If you operate your business as a partnership, control or management of the business is shared. Income and losses are shared among the partners. Each partner is responsible for the debts of the partnership, even if you did not directly incur or cause the debt.
